text: The only people who seemed to enjoy it
those who sleep in her arms
the good Saint Martin , who watches over all travellers , and retraced their steps
the village in which they dwelt
a little child who was asleep
the youngest of their own children was lying
all those who dwelt in the village
the other children of the village
those who were blind or maimed or in any way afflicted
a foul beggar - woman under that fair and green - leaved tree
the Woodcutter , who was cleaving logs in a haggard hard by
no son of thine to do thy bidding
my little son whom I lost in the forest
my little son , whom I bare in the forest
the little daughter of the Woodcutter
the other side of the forest
the beggar - woman who was his mother
the road in front of him
those who dwelt by the way
a strong - walled city that stood by a river
the soldiers who stood on guard
one whose armour was inlaid with gilt flowers , and on whose helmet couched a lion that had wings
the soldiers who it was who had sought entrance
an old and evil - visaged man who was passing by
a garden filled with black poppies and green jars of burnt clay
the subtlest of the magicians of Libya and had learned his art from one who dwelt in the tombs of the Nile
the gate of this city of Giaours
the wood of which the Magician had spoken to him
no one who has pity on me
the cavern that is behind thee
our lord for whom we have been waiting
the child of a poor beggar - woman
the street that led to the gate of the city
the crowd that pressed round the soldiers
the beggar - woman who was his mother , and at her side stood the leper , who had sat by the road
the city that stood by the river he ruled
